{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17603117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17603117"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:32:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:32:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15711"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15711"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0,0,0.16,0.81]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8402"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71480"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8402"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15711"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56989"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7033"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8108"},{"type":"tags","id":"8397"},{"type":"tags","id":"9959"},{"type":"tags","id":"10186"},{"type":"tags","id":"10955"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20243"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20245"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71480"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA microscopic section of fallopian tube tissue shows marked inflammatory infiltrate within the tubal wall. The mucosa appears edematous with numerous neutrophils present. The lumen contains purulent exudate.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Peritubal adhesions","Paratubal cysts","Hydrosalpinx","Chronic salpingitis","Acute salpingitis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe histological features described are classic for \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute salpingitis\u003C/strong\u003E, showing active inflammation characterised by neutrophilic infiltration and mucosal oedema. This represents an acute inflammatory process of the fallopian tube.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeritubal adhesions\u003C/strong\u003E are fibrous bands that form around the fallopian tubes as a result of chronic inflammation or previous surgery, but do not show acute inflammatory changes. \u003Cstrong\u003EParatubal cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are fluid-filled structures adjacent to the fallopian tube that show a simple ciliated epithelial lining without inflammation. \u003Cstrong\u003EHydrosalpinx\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic condition where the fallopian tube is dilated and filled with fluid, showing flattened epithelium rather than acute inflammation. \u003Cstrong\u003EChronic salpingitis\u003C/strong\u003E would show lymphocytic infiltration and fibrosis rather than neutrophilic inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute salpingitis shows inflammatory changes in the fallopian tube wall with neutrophilic infiltration and mucosal edema.","Hydrosalpinx is a chronic condition where the fallopian tube is dilated and filled with fluid, showing flattened epithelium.","Paratubal cysts are benign cysts near but separate from the fallopian tube, lined by ciliated epithelium."],"references":["\u0022Salpingitis - intermed mag\u0022 by Nephron is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license. https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Salpingitis_-_intermed_mag.jpg","van der Putten ME, Engel 